  • in this overview you can see the different correlations between points that the student got and the answers they gave. From this we can say that a positive attitude towards statistics correlated positively with points gained from the course. The other factors did not correlate with statistical significance towards the points

  • Below is a summary of how this data shows the correlation of attitude age and strategical methods towards a course and the results on a linear regression model. The only one that correlates stronly is once again the attitude, However stra and age also seem to have some correlation but not statistically significant.

  • As you see in the summary of a linear model for this data for every scaled point of attitude our expected points increase by 3.52

– note however that the R squared value is only 0.19 which means that our model only accounts for 19% of the variability in the data and thus might not be an accurate method to model this data –> in other words points are only 19% explained by course attitude

  • Lastly we produce some diagnostic plots as in ex2

  • Based on the course book fig 3.4a the Residuals against Fitted values plot shows that our fitted model should be of appropriate quality as there is no clear curvature in our values which would indicate that the model would need transformation.
  • for the standardized residuals we see some potential outliers on the left side which may be the reason why our R-squared is so low. Perhaps there are people who get low scores despite having a good attitude score which lower the predictability ?

  • This dataset consists of the variables shown above taken from students of a math and portuguese class and their performance. Data also has alcohol consumption added to it
  • Daily alcohol consumption Dalc and Weekend alkohol consumption Walc from which alc_use is calculated by taking the average of the two. high_use is True if over the average is over 2 and False if under 2
  • We will use this data to study the relationship between alcohol consumption and other variables in the data

For example if we expect men to be more likely to consume high amounts of alcohol and we want to use this data to test if there is a difference between alcohol consumption (high or low between the genders) we could do it like this

# access the tidyverse packages dplyr and ggplot2
library(dplyr); library(ggplot2)

g1+geom_bar()+facet_wrap("sex")

-Based on this we could say that more men consume high amounts of alcohol when compared to women”

-similarily here is a different type of plot for alcohol usage (high or low) and age - it is expected that alcohol consumption should be low for underage people and that we get more high alcohol use people with higher ages

  • Now we can do logistic regression based analysis on these two examples.

# find the model with glm()
m <- glm(high_use ~ sex, data = alc, family = "binomial")
n <- glm(high_use~age,data=alc,family="binomial")

# print out a summary of the model

## age         1.21426075  0.006116096  0.3847577

  • similarily to above here we also see some correlation between age and high alcohol consumption but this time only 1.2 times as high. Because we are talking of continuous variable such as age every increase in age should raise the odds of being a high alcohol user by 1.2. When we think about it this is not feasible since alcohol consumption does not grow exponentially as we age. so Age might not be a good model even though in this case it is statistically significant. Also to note is that this cohort was partly underage and they cannot legally buy alcohol so data might not be reliable in that sense.

  • Testing the predictitive power of these modesl

probabilities_m <- predict(m, type = "response")
probabilities_n <- predict(n,type = "response")
alc <- mutate(alc, probability_sex = probabilities_m)
alc <- mutate(alc, probability_age = probabilities_n)
#now we have the predictions here and we can use them to predict a treshold of for example 0.5
alc <- mutate(alc, predicted_high_use_sex = ifelse(probability_sex > 0.5, TRUE, FALSE))
alc <- mutate(alc, predicted_high_use_age = ifelse(probability_age > 0.5, TRUE, FALSE))

# Now we can print these into their own 2x2 crosstables to see how they worked

  • For the Sex determining alcohol consumption the model seems to give a few false positives, but it also mislabels a lot of true cases into being false. Thus this model is good at only predicting low alcohol usage. False positive rate = 7/259 = 0.027 –> 2.7% False negative rate 78/111 = 0.70 –> 70%
Alcohol_Age <- table(High_Use=alc$high_use, Prediction=alc$predicted_high_use_age)
print(Alcohol_Age)
##         Prediction
## High_Use FALSE TRUE
##    FALSE   259    0
##    TRUE    110    1

  • This model seems to perform even worse with it only labeling 1 true case correctly but it also labeled all false cases correctly. Though we can probably say that this model predicts almost everything to be False leading it to be correct in the false cases and nothing else. False positive rate = 0/259 = 0 –> 0% False negative rate 110/111 = 0.99 –> 99%

  • All in all both of these models perform rather badly and you could easily perform better by yourself so these models should be tweaked if they would ever to be used.

  • Now we can use the created scaled data with categorical valuables to create training and test data for labeling purposes by dividing our dataset to 80% 20% split between training and test sets
  • we also save the correct classes from our test data for quality control later on and remove the variable crime from the test data -So we use 80% of the data to train our model and 20% of data to do a test to see how accurate our model is.
# number of rows in the Boston dataset 
n <- nrow(boston_scaled)

# choose randomly 80% of the rows
ind <- sample(n,  size = n * 0.8)

# create train set
train <- boston_scaled[ind,]

# create test set 
test <- boston_scaled[-ind,]

# save the correct classes from test data
correct_classes <- test$crime

# remove the crime variable from test data so that we can use our model to label it
test <- dplyr::select(test, -crime)

# the function for lda biplot arrows
lda.arrows <- function(x, myscale = 1, arrow_heads = 0.1, color = "red", tex = 0.75, choices = c(1,2)){
  heads <- coef(x)
  graphics::arrows(x0 = 0, y0 = 0, 
         x1 = myscale * heads[,choices[1]], 
         y1 = myscale * heads[,choices[2]], col=color, length = arrow_heads)
  text(myscale * heads[,choices], labels = row.names(heads), 
       cex = tex, col=color, pos=3)
}

# target classes as numeric
classes <- as.numeric(train$crime)

# plot the lda results (select both lines and execute them at the same time!)
plot(lda.fit, dimen = 2)
lda.arrows(lda.fit, myscale = 1)

- So by looking at the proportion of trace in the summary we can see that 96% of variance between our data can be explained by the first discriminant which means that LD1 is good in distinguishing between classes

  • Now we can save the crime categories from the test set and predict classes with our LDA model on the test data. We previously saved the correct classes so we can use those to validate our model

  • now we can run K-means using our data
set.seed(6)

# determine the number of clusters
k_max <- 5

# calculate the total within sum of squares
twcss <- sapply(1:k_max, function(k){kmeans(boston_scaled, k)$tot.withinss})

# visualize the results
qplot(x = 1:k_max, y = twcss, geom = 'line')

# k-means clustering
km <- kmeans(boston_scaled, centers = 2)

# plot the Boston dataset with clusters
pairs(boston_scaled, col = km$cluster)

- Based on our twcss we can say that the optimal number of clusters is 2 as that is where the value starts dropping drastically, but 3 could also be a valid option to test.

as for the pairs analysis now we see which of the 2 clusters our data labels itself into and we can see that there are a lot of data where one cluster is overrepresented showing that the data lines up with it more.
